<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aburra Militia Demobilizes; Negotiations Continue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2802193294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2802193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] In a scene that looked like something out of a war 
movie, 60 members of the Aburra Valley Militia -- wearing hoods 
and carrying weapons -- traveled from Medellin to Ojevas, Sucre 
Department aboard government helicopters. The action is part of 
the process to reincorporate the Socialist Renewal Movement 
[CRS] into society. 
  At about noon today, the 60 men and women of the People's 
Militia of Aburra Valley were taken in two helicopters to the 
camp at Flor del Monte in Sucre where conversations are underway 
on the demobilization of the CRS. For the time being, these 
talks have not led to any significant agreement. 
  [Begin unidentified CRS member recording] The CRS is an 
organization that operates mainly in the cities. Throughout the 
nation it has 3,000 members, of which only 300 are in arms. That 
is the part we are going to negotiate with the national 
government. [end recording] 
  This is the third group of militias that has decided to go 
to 
negotiations in Medellin. Two other groups are conducting 
negotiations with the state in an area close to Medellin. The 
CRS, leader of these militias in the Aburra Valley, hopes that 
this example of urban disarmament will result in the release of 
200 men who are imprisoned before 3 April when the negotiations 
conclude. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

