<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Expects No Reprisals From Oil Sales to Cuba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0103195894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1815 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0103195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 1 Mar (EFE) -- Mines and Energy 
Minister Guido Nule Amin said today Colombia does not expect 
"reprisals" from Cuban exiles or the United States for the 
announced sale of oil to Cuba. 
  The official, who announced last week the sale of between 
15,000 and 20,000 barrels of oil to Cuba per day, said the oil 
exports will begin in mid-1994. 
  "Cuba's main partners are Mexico and Canada, and it has been 
no cause for problems with the United States," Nule Amin added. 
  The energy and mines minister said he does not see how 
Colombia "could have problems" for selling crude to the island. 
  He explained Colombia will sell that quantity of oil, 
"barely 
one third of the (Cuban) demand for oil." 
  He said the method of payment of these "direct" sales will 
be 
"at international prices, and the Cubans will pay with foreign 
exchange." 
  Meanwhile, it was reported in Santa Fe de Bogota Cuban 
exiles 
in Miami would allegedly boycott Colombian products. 

</TEXT>

