<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canadian Foreign Minister Begins Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Colombian President's OAS Bid Backed </H4>
<F P=102> PA0303231094 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0518 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0303231094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 1 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- On 1 March, Mexican 
Foreign Relations Secretary Manuel Tello and Canadian Foreign 
Affairs Minister Andre Ouellet pledged their support in Mexico 
City for Colombian President Cesar Gaviria's candidacy for OAS 
secretary general. 
  Upon the conclusion of the 10th meeting of the 
Mexican-Canadian Ministerial Commission on 1 March, the two 
officials announced their governments' support for the candidacy 
of the Colombian president, thus adding to the support already 
pledged by the United States, Venezuela, Ecuador, Peru, and 
Argentina, among others. 
  The election of the OAS secretary general will take place in 
Washington, D.C. on 27 March. The new secretary general, who 
will take office on 20 June, must garner at least 18 of the 34 
votes that the members of this hemispheric organization will 
cast. 
  Costa Rican Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus is the other 
candidate with possibilities of occupying the OAS secretary 
general seat. 

</TEXT>

