<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0303215894 </F>
<F P=103> PA0303215894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments relating to the Panamanian elections 
scheduled for 8 May. 
  Ruben Dario Carles, "Change 94" presidential candidate, 
travelled to Colombia where he met with Colombian President 
Cesar Gaviria to discuss economic issues that will 
``undoubtedly'' benefit the socioeconomic development of Panama. 
On this occasion, Carles also met with Argentina's President 
Carlos Menem, who was also visiting Colombia. (Panama City EL 
SIGLO in Spanish 25 Feb 94 pp 16, 17) 
  Carles told LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA that if he is elected 
president on 8 May, he will send a delegation to Washington on 9 
May to renegotiate the U.S. military presence in exchange for 
economic benefits. Carles accused the Democratic Revolutionary 
Party, PRD, of "waging a friendly opposition campaign against 
the government." (Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 
28 Feb 94 p A1) 
  "Change 94" presidential candidate Carles said once he is 
elected president, he will organize a commission to promote 
investments and the creation of jobs. "This commission will be 
placed directly under the president and will be composed of 
representatives from business groups, worker associations, and 
the government. All investment projects will be presented to 
them." (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 
1 Mar 94) 
  Yesterday, Mireya Gruber, Arnulfist Party presidential 
candidate, said that just because a party member meets with an 
official of a former regime does not mean her party wants to 
negotiate with the military. With regard to presidential 
candidate Carles' interest in talking to the military, she 
limited herself to saying: "I imagine that as a politician he 
will want to talk to all sectors." (Panama City LA PRENSA in 
Spanish 26 Feb 94 p 5A) 
  Fernando Manfredo, Papa Egoro vice presidential candidate, 
denied rumors of disagreement with the party's presidential 
candidate Ruben Blades, as has been rumored in political 
circles. Manfredo said: "The voters appear somewhat cynical; 
they are not impressed by those demagogic speeches and false 
promises. I think this is the current campaign's tendency." 
(Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 23 Feb 
94) 
  Yesterday, PRD candidate Ernesto Perez Balladares returned 
from his trip to the United States, where he met with U.S. 
investors. Perez Balladares told the media upon his arrival that 
he had met with the board of directors of the NEW YORK TIMES and 
THE MIAMI HERALD, and contacted the Latin Chamber of Commerce 
and the Miami mayor. Perez Balladares said: "We established ties 
to work jointly in possible investments and trade exchanges 
starting 1 September." (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in 
Spanish 2300 GMT 23 Feb 94) 
  Perez Balladares said that if he wins the May elections he 
will not grant amnesty nor pardon former civilian and military 
collaborators of the former regime, if they have been found 
guilty of committing a crime and sentenced. (Panama City LA 
PRENSA in Spanish 25 Feb 94 p 1A) 
  Perez Balladres travelled to Mexico City to meet with Luis 
Donaldo Colosio, Institutional Revolutionary Party candidate. 
Perez Balladares said: "Had I been president, I would have 
investigated more thoroughly General Torrijos' death." (Panama 
City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 26 Feb 94 p 1) 
  Perez Balladares thinks candidate Carles' offer to solve the 
nation's main problem in 100 days "is an insult to the 
Panamanian people's intelligence." In statements to LA ESTRELLA 
DE PANAMA, Perez Balladares said it was "very irresponsible" to 
request that U.S. military bases remain after 2000. (Panama City 
LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 28 Feb 94 p A1) 
  Presidential candidate Samuel Lewis Galindo of the National 
Consensus Alliance called ``irresponsible'' statements by former 
Health Minister Guillermo Rolla Pimental, who said money used by 
breweries and the PRD in political campaigns are generated by 
money laundering and drug trafficking." (Panama City LA ESTRELLA 
DE PANAMA in Spanish 26 Feb 94 p 1) 
  Although the most recent polls do not favor candidate Lewis 
Galindo, yesterday he admitted he does believe in this type of 
information. In addition, he criticized presidential candidate 
Carles for not "adequately managing" the public debt when he was 
comptroller general. (Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in 
Spanish 26 Feb 94 p A1) 
  Lewis Galindo told LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA that military bases 
must not be offered to the United States if they do not ask for 
them because "one must maintain one's dignity. The public must 
be consulted" regarding any proposal on this issue, said Lewis. 
(Panama City, LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 28 Feb 94 p A1) 
  On 25 February Lewis Galindo presented his state 
modernization program. He hopes to improve the nation's public 
administration with the program. Lewis Galindo said: "We must 
put our house in order. Those who think that because they have 
personal contacts and relationships, they can obtain funds and 
credits are making a serious error and are mistaken. Until we 
have a modern, flexible state that does not hinder local 
investors, much less foreign investors, we will not achieve 
anything." (Panama City Telemetro Television Network in Spanish 
1730 GMT 28 Feb 94) 
  Four of the seven Panamanian presidential candidates 
participated in the inauguration of CADE 94, the Annual 
Conference of Business Executives, today in Bambito, Chiriqui 
province under the slogan, Concrete Alternatives for Development 
of the Western Part of the Nation, that is, Chiriqui and Bocas 
del Toro. Ruben Dario Carles, "Change 94" candidate, denied 
accusations that he had paid international financial 
institutions. Samuel Lewis Galindo, National Consensus Alliance 
candidate; Eduardo Vallarino, Christian Democratic Party 
candidate; and Ernesto Perez Balladares, PRD candidate, spoke in 
the afternoon. Mireya de Gruber, Arnulfist Candidate; Ruben 
Blades, Papa Egoro candidate; and Salvador Munoz, Panamenist 
Doctrinate Party candidate, sent messages saying they would not 
participate in the conference. (Panama City Circuito RPC 
Television in Spanish 1730 GMT 26 Feb 94) 
  Electoral Tribunal President Guillermo Marquez estimates 
that 
between 350,000 to 375,000 voters will not go to the polls on 8 
May. Recent polls indicate that 20 to 25 percent of the voters 
will not vote. Marquez indicated that 40 to 50 international 
observers will be present at the 8 May elections. (Panama City 
LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 1 Mar 94 p 1) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

