<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `CA-3 Group' To Negotiate Accord With Mexico </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0503023694 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2200 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0503023694 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 4 Mar (ACAN-EFE) -- Guatemalan 
Foreign Trade Minister Eduardo Gonzalez said the free trade 
treaty that Costa Rica and Mexico will sign in April will serve 
as an example and as a foundation for negotiations by the 
Central American Northern Triangle, formed by Guatemala, El 
Salvador, and Honduras. 
  The Guatemalan official told ACAN-EFE that the Mexican-Costa 
Rican agreement is "positive" and added that "we have been 
closely following the process that Costa Rica was carrying out 
with Mexico." Nevertheless, he said Guatemala has decided along 
with Honduras and El Salvador, which form the so-called CA-3 
[Central America-3] group, to jointly negotiate an economic 
agreement with Mexico. "The agreement between Costa Rica and 
Mexico will serve as an example and a foundation for the 
negotiations" that will be held with the Mexican authorities, he 
said. Gonzalez announced that the CA-3 technical groups will 
meet in El Salvador on 7 and 8 March to continue analyzing a 
joint mechanism for an economic complementation agreement with 
Mexico, which jointly with the United States and Canada forms 
the world's biggest economic bloc. 
  Ministers of the three Central American countries are 
scheduled to meet with their Mexican counterpart, Herminio 
Blanco [name as received], on 11 March to analyze the marketing 
obstacles that some products of the region have in Mexico. 
  Gonzalez said efforts will be made to have the closer trade 
ties with Mexico lead to Central America's integration into the 
NAFTA. 

</TEXT>

