<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRI Members Partially Burn Municipal Palace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0603011994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2315 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0603011994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 5 Mar (EFE) -- Today some 100 members 
of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) partially burned 
the municipal palace at Teoloyucan, 50 km north of the Mexican 
capital, to demand the dismissal of Mayor Pedro Zenteno, who 
belongs to the opposition Party of the Democratic Revolution 
(PRD). 
  The PRI members have gathered at the central plaza and are 
armed with sticks and stones under the surveillance of the 
police who have not intervened up until now, according to 
sources from the municipality of Teoloyucan, which has a 
population of 52,000. 
  Pedro Zenteno, the municipal mayor of Teoloyucan, told EFE 
that the municipal palace was looted, some windows were 
shattered, and part of the building was set on fire by the PRI 
members. 
  Zenteno was appointed municipal mayor of Teoloyucan by the 
Congress of the State of Mexico on 25 January, after 
participating in the municipal elections on 14 November. 
  The PRD leader in the state of Mexico, Gerardo Fernandez 
Norona, told EFE that the situation in Teoloyucan "is delicate" 
because the state government "has had difficulties in enforcing 
the decisions of the congress." We know that "behind the group 
of PRI members are strong interests and chieftains, who have 
even clashed with Mexico State Governor Emilio Chuayffet Chemor. 
  The PRI spokesman in the state of Mexico, Eleazar Flores 
Arriaga, told EFE: "We know there is a group of people who are 
unhappy with the acting mayor; we do not know if they are PRI 
members. I could not say for sure." He denied that the municipal 
palace was burned and said a fire only broke out in the attic, 
where a group of persons looted some offices. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

