<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canadian Foreign Minister Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on Meeting </H4>
<F P=102> PA0403190194 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0403190194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Lourdes Esquivel; from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Secretary Manuel Tello closed the 10th 
Mexican-Canadian Ministerial Meeting in Mexico City. The 
Canadian ministers and the Mexican secretaries and deputy 
secretaries comprised four groups that analyzed the possibility 
of bilateral cooperation in the transportation, agriculture, 
environment, and commerce sectors. 
  Mexican Communications and Transportation Secretary Emilio 
Gamboa and Canadian Transportation Minister Douglas Young signed 
three transportation agreements that will allow reciprocal entry 
to drivers who carry products; the bilateral recognition of 
commercial drivers' licenses; and technical cooperation in 
training programs. 
  Canadian Foreign Minister Andre Ouellet and Secretary Manuel 
Tello discussed regional and global politics. The Canadian 
foreign minister termed as surprising the efforts exerted to 
make the process as democratic as possible and said Canada 
believes in the political and social future of Mexico. Minister 
Ouellet also referred to the Chiapas conflict. He said Canada 
supports the actions carried out by the Mexican Government and 
encourages President Salinas de Gortari to continue along the 
same path. The Canadian foreign minister and Secretary Tello 
supported Colombian President Cesar Gaviria's candidacy for OAS 
secretary general Secretariat and they reasserted their support 
for the lifting of the blockade in Cuba. 
  The next ministerial meeting will be held in Canada in 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

