<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serra Praises Free Trade Accord With Costa Rica </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0603044594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0342 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0603044594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 4 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Mexican Commerce 
Secretary Jaime Serra Puche referred to the free trade agreement 
with Costa Rica, whose negotiation will conclude this week, as 
"the most advanced in Latin America." Serra Puche argued that 
the agreement not only includes goods but also services, 
copyrights and investments, dispute settlement procedures, and 
government purchases." [no beginning quotation mark as received] 
  Mexico and Costa Rica trade goods and services for some $80 
million a year. Serra Puche believes that the treaty negotiated 
with Costa Rica, which will come into force on 1 January 1995, 
could become a very useful guideline for negotiations with other 
Central American countries. He pointed out that talks with 
Central America will continue, but they "will not be conducted 
as a bloc." Therefore, there will be separate negotiations with 
Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras, and later with Nicaragua. 
  Serra Puche announced that trade negotiations with the Group 
of Three -- Mexico, Venezuela, and Colombia -- might resume in 
March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

