<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0403034294 </F>
<F P=103> PY0403034294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 3 
March. 
  The Central Bank has reported that the Uruguayan public 
sector's gross foreign debt increased $33 million, or 0.8 
percent, and that the net foreign debt dropped 4.1 percent in 
the first 11 months of 1993. The gross foreign debt was $4.1688 
billion late in November, $35 million less than late in October, 
because of a drop in the public financial sector's debt. 
(Madrid EFE in Spanish 2010 GMT 24 Feb 94) 
  The National Statistics Institute on 2 March reported that 
the consumer price index rose 1.43 percent in February, the 
lowest monthly rate since December 1987. The cumulative 
inflation rate for the last 12 months was 48.96 percent, the 
best rate since April 1984. Health care registered the highest 
increase, with 3.93 percent; housing 2.19 percent, and 
recreation 1.77 percent. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 2112 GMT 2 Mar 
94) 

</TEXT>

