<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Explains Tax Collection Changes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0403214494 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0403214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cecilia Pachano; from "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The president hopes that the implementation of the 
so-called Sosa Plan will bring in 400 billion bolivares. The 
Sosa Plan comprises five changes to the country's current tax 
collection system. These changes are: taxes on luxury and 
wholesale items, which will replace the VAT [Value Added Tax], 
and modification of laws covering fiscal stamps, tax code, 
income tax, and a temporary tax on bank debits. All of these 
will allow the president, according to the finance minister, to 
collect about 400 billion boliavares and reduce the fiscal 
deficit to 2 percent of the GNP. 
  During his talks, Finance Minister Dr. Julio Sosa Rodriguez 
explained that the tax on bank deposits would be effective only 
up to 31 December and will yield 75 billion bolivares in six 
months. 
  [Begin Sosa recording] It is a type of tax that one would 
not 
like to have permanently, but we have seen the results in other 
countries where it has been applied. Therefore, what we are 
going to propose is a figure, which I believe when applied for a 
limited amount of time will not adversely affect savings. [end 
recording] 
  The finance minister also expressed satisfaction with the 
establishment of the fiscal police. According to the 
Comptroller General's Office, current tax evasion hovers around 
70 percent. It is hoped that with this new organization, tax 
evasion will be reduced to at least 50 percent. 
  The finance minister also mentioned he did not understand 
the 
Senate's objection to Carlos Tinoco's candidacy to head Fogade 
[Deposit Guarantee Fund] -- a candidacy proposed by the 
president; nevertheless, Sosa said he would heed the decision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

