<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry May Take Action </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0503010394 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 4 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0503010394 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "the Voz Andes Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The Ecuadoran Foreign Ministry will take whatever 
diplomatic measures are warranted with regard to U.S. Ambassador 
Peter Romero's remarks on the Peruvian-Ecuadoran territorial 
dispute. The Foreign Ministry made this statement after Foreign 
Minister Diego Paredes met with the U.S. diplomat, who was 
summoned to explain the remarks he made in an interview 
published by the Guayaquil press. The diplomat said that the 
Ecuadoran people are not prepared to recover their territory by 
the use of arms. 
  The official Ecuadoran statement after the meeting limited 
itself to reporting that the ambassador had been called for 
consultations. Paredes indicated that his office will adopt 
whatever diplomatic measures are warranted and will issue a 
communique in this regard. The Ecuadoran foreign minister 
underscored that Ecuador is very respectful of the internal 
situations of other countries and expects the same treatment. 

</TEXT>

