<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bomb Injures Five At Barranquilla Rally </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0703034394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0021 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0703034394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 6 Mar (EFE) -- Authorities 
reported that at least five people were injured today, Sunday, 
when two unidentified people on a motorcycle threw a bomb into 
the "Rancho Tropical" pavilion in Barranquilla, northern 
Colombia. Senator Fuad Char Abdala had just left the scene when 
the bomb exploded. According to the polls, Fuad Char Abdala is 
the Liberal Party candidate who will receive the most votes in 
the 13 March legislative elections. Char Abdala had presided 
over the closing ceremony for his political campaign at the 
aforementioned location. 
  The "Rancho Tropical" in southern Barranquilla was destroyed 
by the fire sparked by the bomb. Owner Guillermo Min told the 
police that he had no enemies, thus he believes that the attack 
was aimed at Char Abdala. The senator was the development 
minister between 1988 and 1990 and now hopes to be reelected to 
the Senate. 
  Fortunately the bomb was thrown 30 minutes after the 
political event had ended, and the liberal leader's followers 
had already left the scene. The five people who were injured 
sustained minor cuts when several windows were broken. The 
individuals were taken to a medical center, where it was 
determined that none had suffered serious injuries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

