<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Greiff Regrets Church Talks With Guerrillas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0503182494 Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 1 Mar 
94 p 9A </F>

<F P=103> PA0503182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff says he regrets 
the fact that members of the Catholic Church are holding 
permanent talks with the guerrillas. De Greiff was referring to 
San Gil Bishop Monsignor Leonardo Gomez' admission to having 
held such meetings. 
  In statements to the Colmundo Radio Network, the official 
said: "I think it is regrettable that a bishop has become a 
mailbox for subversives." 
  The prelate said on 24 February that he met "with the FARC 
[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia] 23d Front." He also 
said this guerrilla organization "did not perpetrate some crimes 
attributed to it in Velez Province; paramilitary groups did." 
  De Greiff responded to those statements. When asked about 
the legal repercussions for such actions, he said that "one 
characteristic of the state of law is that no one is above the 
law, not even the most dignified person. No one can feel free 
to dictate his own behavioral guidelines." 
  De Greiff added: "If the law that Colombians have approved 
forbids talking with subversives, then everybody must obey it: 
the president of the Republic, the bishops, and even the most 
humble Colombian." 
  Two months ago, on 17 January, Santander authorities blamed 
the 23d Front for perpetrating a bloody and vicious attack on 
the Florian community that left five policemen dead. 
  On August 1993, the National Committee of Victims of the 
Guerrillas [Comite Nacional de Victimas de la Guerrilla] (Vida), 
headed by lawyer Fernando Vargas, personally filed charges 
against Bishop Gomez at the Prosecutor General's Office for 
allegedly being an accomplice to and aiding and abetting the 
subversives. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

