<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Settlement Plan Backed by Employers, CONACOM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0703190494 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0703190494 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] They are all for the Washington plan except the 
people's organizations, perhaps those very close to the 
president in exile. The political crisis settlement plan that 
arose from the Washington negotiations and was approved by a 
majority of deputies in a parliamentary session on 2 March seems 
to be gathering a maximum of support. The Haitian employer 
sector also is backing the document for which CONACOM [National 
Congress Of Democratic Movements], a party close to the 
president in exile, also gave its support to the parliament. The 
other political parties are still waiting and have refrained 
from taking a stand on what the U.S. Embassy spokesman in 
Port-au-Prince sees as a step toward the exit door in this long, 
Haitian crisis. 

</TEXT>

