<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Refuses Ties With `Any' De Facto Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0803010694 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0803010694 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The visit by (Michael Cozac), the assistant to 
President Clinton's special representative in the Haitian 
crisis, has come to an end. (Cozac) had arrived in 
Port-au-Prince over the weekend for the purpose of holding 
conversations with personalities involved in finding a solution 
to the crisis. Mr. (Cozac) termed the situation in Haiti 
encouraging. He made the Haitian military responsible for the 
reimposition of the sanctions. He explained that if the military 
respected their commitments within the scope of the Governors 
Island agreement, the sanctions would be lifted. He further said 
that the U.S. Government wants the Haitian Army to be 
professional and apolitical. 
  Furthermore, Mr. (Cozac) said that the Haitian 
parliamentarians' plan is a good and serious effort to 
disentangle the democratic process. In his opinion, the plan 
must not replace the Governors Island agreement, and the United 
States does not wish to impose a plan on President Aristide or 
to require from him actions not provided for by the 3 July 
agreement. Finally, Mr. (Cozac) gave the following warning, 
quote: The U.S. Government will not have relations with any de 
facto governments in Haiti, unquote. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

