<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chiapas Indians, Peasants Demand Solution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0703160294 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
1300 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0703160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Juan Sebastian Solis; from the "Good Morning From </F>
Mexico" newscast] 
  [Text] Approximately 5,000 representatives of 40 Indian and 
peasant groups in Chiapas State marched through the streets of 
San Cristobal de las Casas on Sunday to demand solutions to 
problems involving land, justice, freedom, and democracy. The 
march, which was organized by the state committee of Indian and 
peasant organizations, was also supported by 300 teachers from 
Oaxaca. Some of the groups were formed solely by women. The 
Mexican flag was carried by Indian women. 
  The demonstrators gathered in front of the municipal 
building 
and held a four-hour rally in which representatives of each of 
the participating organizations spoke. Mrs. Marcela Gonzalez 
spoke on behalf of the Emiliano Zapata Peasant Organization 
[Organizacion Campesina Emiliano Zapata]. She said: 
  [Begin Gonzalez recording] We are standing up for Indian 
dignity, and no one is going to bring us to our knees. [end 
recording] 
  The demonstrators demanded the reform of Article 27 of the 
Constitution, a solution to the problem of delinquent loans, 
dismissal of mayors in Chiapas, and respect for Indian 
traditions and cultures. As they marched through the city, the 
demonstrators wrote their demands on the walls of houses and 
stores. They did the same on the walls of the San Cristobal de 
las Casas municipal building. 

</TEXT>

