<F P=100> Paraguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colorado Party Appeals Party Elections Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0503175094 Asuncion ULTIMA HORA in Spanish 4 Mar 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> PY0503175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ULTIMA HORA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today lawyer Jaime Jose Bestard, acting on behalf of 
the Colorado Reconciliation Movement, a faction of the Colorado 
Party, submitted to the Supreme Court a great number of 
documents on the Colorado Party elections, which were held on 27 
December 1992. These documents could allegedly prove that the 
current administration of President Juan Carlos Wasmosy is 
illegitimate. Luis Maria Argana, the leader of the faction, also 
was present at the Supreme Court when the presentation was made. 
  The Supreme Court received five thick binders which contain 
5,000 notarized photocopies of electoral records from the 
capital, Concepcion, San Pedro, Cordillera, Guaira, Caaguazu, 
Caazapa, Itaugua, Itapua, Misiones, Paraguari and Alto Parana. 
The records bear the signatures of the presidents, vice 
presidents, and faction representatives of each voting station. 
  The plea states: "These documents clearly show the true 
results of the Colorado Party elections held on 27 December 
1992." 
  According to the plea, the total vote count yields the 
following result: Ticket No. 4 [Argana] 215,764 votes; Ticket 
No. 2 [Wasmosy] 188,949 votes, which means that the Colorado 
Reconciliation Movement won the elections by 26,815. 
  It is explained that only the vote counts for presidential 
and vice presidential candidates are being objected to as 
unconstitutional, not the vote count for senators and deputies. 
  The plea emphasizes that "it is aimed at laying bare this 
monstrous fraud and paving the way for the appropriate criminal 
lawsuit and claims for damages against the people involved." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

