<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polls Show Candidates Samper, Pastrana Tied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0703194194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0703194194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Ernesto Samper and Andres Pastrana are tied in their 
bid for the Presidency of the Republic. According to the latest 
poll by the National Consulting Center, the two candidates, who 
lead the surveys, are still neck and neck for the first and 
second round of elections. 
  Samper and Pastrana are advancing neck and neck in their 
quest for the Presidency. For the first time in history, no 
bets can be made for either candidate in the electoral process. 
The polls have revealed such a small difference that it can be 
said technically they are tied. 
  Figures speak for themselves. For the first electoral round 
Samper obtained 38 percent of the support over 37 percent for 
Pastrana; forty-five percent of those polled in the second round 
have said they would vote for Andres Pastrana and 44 percent for 
Ernesto Samper. 
  Regardless of from where it comes, the opinion sector or the 
campaign team, the fact of the matter is in May each vote will 
be decisive. There are eight weeks before the election, 
however, and the result of the consultation within the Liberal 
Party and the reallocation of forces after the legislative 
elections can change things substantially. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-10488 </DOCNO>
